<DOC><DOCNO> AP901221-0091 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NY-12-21-90 1235EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-NativityDispute     12-21 0166</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Nativity Dispute,0174</SECOND><HEAD>Judge Waits Until Day After Christmas To Hear Arguments To RemoveCreche</HEAD><DATELINE>MONTEREY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The dispute over whether a Nativityscene should remain in front of City Hall this holiday season maybe moot by the time a judge gets around to hearing arguments - oneday after Christmas.   A federal judge in San Jose has agreed to hear arguments Dec. 26to decide whether the wood-carved manger scene implies governmentalendorsement of Christianity over other faiths.   In similar cases, the U.S. Supreme Court has allowed Nativityscenes or other religious displays when they were surrounded byother secular holiday decorations.   The Monterey display, depicting the birth of Jesus, had been atraditional holiday decoration outside City Hall for nearly 30years until 1989 when it was moved to a Roman Catholic church toavoid a legal dispute.   But this year the Nativity scene went back up outside City Hall,prompting the American Civil Liberties Union and Victor Ringel, a13-year-old Jewish boy, to sue.</TEXT></DOC>